Following are major news items in leading Japanese newspapers
today: Asahi, Nihon Keizai: -- Japan's National Police Agency is
preparing to tighten the firearms control law to prevent crimes
involving guns. Asahi, Mainichi, Yomiuri, Nihon Keizai: -- South Korean
President Kim Young-sam told Japanese Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama
in Copenhagen yesterday that he is concerned over Japan's sending a
mission to Pyongyang in hopes of reopening bilateral talks on
normalization of diplomatic relations between Japan and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea. Kim said he is also concerned over moves
against an anti-war resolution the Japanese Diet (parliament) is
considering. Yomiuri: -- Prime Minister Murayama told the U.N. Summit
on Social Development yesterday that Japan will concentrate its
official development aid on social development projects.
